,Recommended,249650,22889810,"Posted: 9 May, 2016",all,Draetor,"I honestly took a long time to play this game (I knew I eventually would as I love turn based tactical RPG), because of all the mixed reviews.  Regardless, I can't believe how much fun the combat in this game is.  I'll break down some key game concepts that might persuade you to buy or push you away.Good:-Amazing character development using a deep system of random dice rolls and old-school board game elements-Hard battles (some are pushovers) that make you think or have to re-do because of a single screw up-Deep turn based hexagonal board-like combat involving traps and the environment-A Baldur's Gate style of map minus the exploration-The game really focuses on the battles without the fuss of wandering and exploring (ie. not an exploration game)Bad:-The story is not bad, but one shouldn't be getting this game for that reason-The itemization and game mechanics are a bit complicated to understand and required a lot of Google searching-Linear story and no explorationIf you are looking for a game that focuses purely on the tactical turn based combat, then this is truly it.  There is no wandering and exploring with your party and discovering secrets.  The world map is like Baldur's Gate, however, when you visit cities and places, you are either transported into a combat situation with some cutscenes or visit a town where NPC's are static screens filled with innkeepers, healers, merchants, etc."
,Recommended,249650,21922036,"Posted: 19 March, 2016",all,SpiteAndMalice,"I'm really surprised at some of the negative reviews that this game has received.I personally found the story to be interesting and engaging, it's dark in places and you need to get your hands dirty, but that's how Dark Eye fantasy generally is. One moment in particular seems to have turned some players off, I thought it was a brave decision by the developers, and I thought it worked well, a story should generate emotion, and this one did. It's not all grim and dark however, and the humour is very finely tuned in places.Turn based tactical games are a genre that I'm very much into, I play a lot of Chaos Reborn on a daily basis for the PvP side of it. Consequentially I often find that with story driven turn based tactical games that the PvE battles are a let-down, I don't think an AI can generally replicate the engagement that comes from playing against a human opponent. But I tell you what, Blackguards comes as close to it as I've ever found. There's a real wealth of variation in the battles that occur from; small skirmishes, arena fights, fighting withdraws, chase downs, there's all sorts. The developers of Blackguards have really gone out of their way to keep the fighting fresh. As a result this is one story driven turn based tactical game that I can see myself replaying. Just taken on their own the fights are a lot of fun.I think the one caveat that I'd give is that this is a game where it's worth checking out what happens to certain characters in advance. I’m not going to give anyway any spoilers here, but making your party build based on that knowledge does make a difference to the overall effectiveness of your party by the end of the game."
