,Recommended,249650,26583190,"Posted: 13 November, 2016",all,Felipepepe,"Known for old-school point & click adventure games such as Deponia and Edna & Harvey, German developer Daedalic took gamers by surprise when releasing Blackguards – a tactical turn-based RPG based on The Dark Eye tabletop ruleset.While the story sells itself as a dark narrative where you play as outlaws, it’s rather cliche and heroic. The Dark Eye ruleset is the true drawing point. While some rules where cut, such as most non-combat talents, it remains a solid and complex (if rather intimidating) classless system, offering ample freedom when creating your character. It’s a joy for hardcore players, but very poorly explained for newcomers. Sadly, the forced party members end up limiting some of your party building possibilities – sometimes even forcing a restart.Blackguards knows its limitations and uses some unconventional design choices to compensate them, betting everything on its battles – cities are presented as simple animated backgrounds with stores and NPCs to talk with, exploration is limited to a 2D world map full of icons, dungeons are but a semi-linear sequence of battles without rest and the story is told via simple cutscenes, with an occasional decision to be made. This leads to an unique “Western Final Fantasy Tactics” feel, and while the game first hours are very linear, it later opens up to a wide range of interesting side-quests.Daedalic’s background as an adventure game developer is felt here in an unusual way. There are no random battles in Blackguards, meaning that every encounter happens in an unique arena specifically designed for it, often with unique challenges or tactical puzzles. There are traps, time limits, holes that spawn enemies, movable and destructible objects, healing orbs, falling chandeliers, mechanical blades, flying dragons, swamp gas, giant tentacles, mind-controlling plants, draw bridges, collapsing passageways, a giant cage on a crane, etc.There’s not a single RPG out there that offers so many interesting combat scenarios. This alone makes Blackguards a must-play for any tactical fan – or RPG designer.Unfortunately, the game stretches out for far too long (40 to 60 hours), and the limited variety of enemies and equipment result in a rather stale second half of the game. Still, fans of Tactical RPGs will have a blast."
76561197995669628,Recommended,249650,23368856,"Posted: 3 June, 2016",all,Sorokonojka,"BlackGuards is a turn based RPG with party combat and grid battlegrounds . It is not open world game but rather simplified system where you move around towns and map by clicking on images .There are some sidequests and text based choices that can effect quest outcome and impact later in game . At the start you will be able to customize your character in depth with skills but cosmetic options are lacking .This game has a lot of issues but I was able to overlook those because the core gameplay is fun and challenging . I will go over some negative points that people mentioned in reviews to give some feedback .-Beginner's trap?-There are several events in this game that can force you to start over if you did not manage your resources properly . You can end up in a position where you can't win a fight and can't go to previous areas to level up on side quests .  Auto Save will not help so you should keep 2 more save points .I don't think that it adds any fair difficulty but I like games that do not hold my hand .This game is extremely hard because you can't always anticipate what happens . Like you may need a speed buff for a mission but you never got it . There are many fights where I had to go back to get the right skills and come back (which is not always an option) . If you are a casual gamer there is a chance you might get stack because you did not build characters correctly .I am seasond RPG player and this was the most unforgiving game I ever played .-Permadeath on Party Characters-?One of the characters in your party will die ( forever ) This is a scripted event so you won't actually loose party members by diying in combat  . It is kinda cool to see a game have the balls to do that but for obvious reasons not everybody likes that . You can potentially waste some gold by buying equipment for that character ( I think you get it back but sellback value is not the same ) The real problem is that you may waste some of your Skill points thinking that you can rely on this character for a specific role .- Too much Luck -?-In this game Ranged,Melee and Spell attacks have % to hit . Luck is a big factor early on  . Eventually you can upgrade skills high enough to where you will hit 90-100% so it has to do a lot with how you level your characters .Dodging is frustraing early in game but not a fair criticism for RPG because it adds depth to character builds . However there is a luck element to using items from iventory which can be avoided by save/load ( so that mechanic just wastes your time )-Very basic loot System -Loot in this game is not exciting to say the least . You get a 3-7 damage weapon and 10 hours later you get 4-8 weapon .It keeps number values low which is good because it makes fights less gear dependent but I would prefer something better than just common white trash as you would call it in other games .Rewards for Side quests are very unbalanced . Some quest chains can take 2-3 hours and you might get the same reward as the 20 minute quest . There are some specific quests that give uniqe weapons but there is no consistency with legth or difficulty of the mission .I also should address god awful inventory weight system . This game kinda requires you to carry a lot of gear especially toward late game but you never have enough inventory space . Like entire game I was between 90 and 100% full . You constantly have to find items to remove even though you do not have that much junk .-Pros ?-Challenging tactical gameplayGood variety of different stages and objectivesText choices that impact later in gameSpells that gain new effect at maximum levelDecent voice acting and some good jokes .Score: 7/10 . I am really enjoying the unpredictable and unforgiving nature of this game . Perhaps it is a bit unfair  to new and casual players but it is fantastic for someone who does not want the game to hold your hand . At full price I would not recommend it to everyone but on sale you should consider picking it up if you like turn based party RPGs ."
