,Recommended,249650,8953470,"Posted: 2 February, 2014",all,Harrison11106,"From the trailers one is given the impression that you're playing the roles of the ""bad guys"" for once but have to ""save the world"";  a more apt analogy would be to say that the characters would probably fit well into the world of the former T.V shows Breaking Bad & Sci fis Battlestrar Galactica.  Does each character have skeletons, of course but I've yet to see one that actually warrents a ""Blackguard"" title; in fairness here the Blackguard definition, a-la from Dungeons & Dragons, is in a different context then from this title.As has been stated in other reviews & fromDaedelic Entertainment, the game is based off a tabletop role-playing game from Germany. This is my first foray into this system in any case.  The story is OK, but not much more then that.  You don't gain levels per se, but you gain adventure points (AP) when either defeating foes or completing a quest.  You use these points to raise just about everything pertaining to your character, be it statistics, your skills, your resitances, & for magic users how effective spells are & the astral points needed to cast them.  The higher the ""level"" of the STATS, skills etc, the more AP they cost.  Unfortunately, I've not come into any battle where my group has had a ""windfall"" of AP, so far  I've either gotten 30, 60 or around 120 AP depending on the battle (whether mundane foes or major ones).   I've gotten a bit more AP when completing quests though. In fairness here I'm playing it on the easiest difficulty, maybe battles give you more AP on the harder ones, though I doubt it.The hightlights of the game are the battle system, I've yet to encounter any ""cut & paste"" battle area.  The upgrade system for your characters is fairly subtle, but noticable for the most part.  In short, you don't feel like you're spending AP to upgrade your character & they don't feel like they're more powerful.   The spells are diverse & effective. Mapwise there is a fairly large area to cover in both the in battle maps & world map.The weaknesses of the game, thus far are:No areas to really grind for AP,with possible exception of arena, but even there I believe you can only have a certain amount of battles in the arena.  You can't actually make things, not armor or weapons, at least not at the point in the game that I'm at.  There's no height or lowlands difference in battles; in short I've not had so much as 1 battle where either I or the enemy started at the top of a hill.  I've also yet to have been involved in a battle where I've gotten a huge amount of AP. I'm roughly at the halfway mark, going by what the creators wrote on the main page, but I've yet to see so much as one magical item, whether defensive or offensive item.  I don't know the tabletop RPG this is based off of so perhaps the world lacks magical items or if they're simply more subtle in nature when compared to games like Final Fantasy Tactics.   The spellcasters also need work, I find them more useful as party ""buffers"", and from what I've read on the forums I'm in the nearly overwhelming majority.This game needs some minor tweaks to really grab you & keep you in it's grip; but so far any issues I have with it, in the scheme of things, are relatively minor & not game breaking."
76561198018106356,Recommended,249650,8237437,"Posted: 23 December, 2013",all,greenbean,"This is my first early access game.  I had reservations, but so far I put in a few hours into it. It's fun, there are some mechanics that are not as intuitive, and I'm early on in the game.  For instance buying weapons.  Would be nice when buying a new sword, that it would list all the characters that can use that sword and their +- stats if they were to buy that sword. Hoping for more weapon variety in upcoming patches.  The game is sufficiently challenging.  Gold is hard to come by so items you purchase can be frustrating at times. If you spent all your money on an axe, you just happen to find during the next battle for instance.  But that's the nature of the beast I guess.  The battles are a bit more like HOMM vs xcom.   Overall, I would recommend this game! Good turn based strategy games are hard to come by so lets support them!  btw Bellarita mission =  Worse most frustrating mission ever."
76561198061936119,Recommended,249650,11313487,"Posted: 18 July, 2014",all,miggi85,"Blackguards is an interesting turn based game. It is ultimately focused more on preparation than on actual strategy in combat. Generally speaking basic resource management and a bit of luck when it comes to the (sometimes infuriating) RNG will win fights.I found the poison & trapping elements of Blackguards to be more to it's detriment than benefit, with poisons and traps being prohibitively expensive both in terms of currency and the use of a turn to apply them and a belt slot to carry them. Most enemies are immune or highly resilient to poison and trap effects, and there are many enemies which will poison you with debuffs for the whole battle if they land a hit. The only spell which works to remove poison is ineffective against the stonger poisons, which by endgame most enemies use. Overall a couple of unlucky dodge/parry rolls and a couple of unlucky attack rolls will result in your whole party being poisoned and the battle becoming much more difficult.Blackguards has a very deep character development system, with many core stats which affect different battle stats. The game could have benefited from fewer weapon skills and perhaps a poison resistance skill, however overall I found the stat system worthwhile.The final act is very padded - there is substatially more combat than previous acts and it can get a little dry. Overall I enjoyed my time with Blackguards but was happy to be finished - usually a sign that something that was fun in the beginning got a bit tedious.I would say if you like turn based RPGs, give Blackguards a go."
