76561198081858314,Recommended,249650,8965709,"Posted: 3 February, 2014",all,fernandofitch,"I'm only about 4-5 hours into it but this is great! The combat system reminds me of king's bounty, or maybe Heroes of Might and Magic where your characters are on a hex grid and you move then attack/ability. It has the feel of a proper RPG though, with various attributes/skills/powers that have points put into them that are subsequently used in the fights. The out of combat system isn't as interactive as, say, fallout 3 or skyrim or something. It's almost exclusively chatboxes accompanying a thumbnail picture of the speaker while there is a static background image, like many JRPGs (especially back in the day), and there is a map with nodes on it to which you may travel but you don't run around freely looking for stuff. Personally I don't consider that a drawback per se but others might. I can't say for sure how much your choices effect the story because I'm too early in the game, but the element of your choices mattering seems to be there, for example *spoiler* there are twin brothers that want to kill each other and you can choose if or which one you help them kill and you fight different battles and get different rewards depending on which one you choose. It's a sidequest though so I'm not certain it's a big deal.Anyway great game! Definitely worth the buy!"
76561198024080920,Recommended,249650,8970345,"Posted: 3 February, 2014",all,Inzu,"Great game, lots of fun.  Well worth the money if you are into tactical, turn-based combat.The characters and voice acting are top notch.  The dialogue witty.Character advancement is done by earning adventure points that you apply to the skills and stats you wish to improve. There's no set levels. The more skilled or powerful you are at something, the more adventure points it costs to improve that skill or stat further.  It makes it impossible to make a character that is unbeatable at everything, so you really need to put some thought into party roles and utilizing each character's strengths and weaknesses.Most of the battlefields have static and dynamic features that can add an advantage to your party or spell their doom. This keeps combat interesting.One thing I found fun, but some might find frustrating is that you don't get to choose where your characters start on the battlefield.  For the most part, your characters are started in such a logical position that you don't even question it, but every now and then a battle is added with your characters scattered all over the place. Sometimes it makes sense within the story line, sometimes not.The enemy AI does fairly well as an opponent. While it doesn't always use the battlefield features to full advantage, it does it often enough to keep you on your toes.Overall, two thumbs up !One thing to note - if you are the kind of player that has to have tons of sparkly, magical loot, this game is not for you.If you are the kind of player that needs to have five sets of armor, fifteen weapons, and a house with fifty chests to store all those weapons and armor in, this game is not for you.  Gear upgrades are mundane and modest, and you'll have the same armor and weapons with you for large portions of the game.  Encumbrance penalties dissuade you from carrying much more than the armor on your back and the weapons on your person.The game is more about tactics and skills than it is about loot."
