76561198006167184,Recommended,249650,18562659,"Posted: 18 October, 2015",all,Cerandal,"Before saying anything else: this is a hard game. Getting to know how everything works may require time, and you will feel frustrated sometimes when your attacks or spells fail again and again. But that also can make it satisfying when you manage to do things well! So, knowing that, if you feel brave enough... go for it!The game can be a bit expensive for its real content, but I would surely recommend getting it on sale. Combat system's really good, you'll depend on strategies and using the environment to get some advantage. Characters are not very developed but are unusual and funny in many scenes, and the story is... well, a bit different, though it has its cliches.Be careful when designing your main character! You'll probably end up failing your first game hard and noticing he's useless when it's too late... Start with an archer if you feel lost - you can't go wrong with that.Pros+ Tactic and varied combat, with lots of maps and strategies+ Fully voiced, good dialogues+ Many different weapons, spells and items you can use during the fights+ Shady characters, not your classic heroes+ More content than I expected, with a lot of sidequests+ A real challenge if you want to go into the hard mode... or even normal difficulty+ One of the best dwarfs everCons- Some fights can be really hard compared to the rest of the game- Learning curve? More like learning wall- You won't understand how combat works until you've failed a lot- Game controls feel a bit clumsy sometimes, you may end up casting heals on yourself instead of the intended target- The ending doesn't live up to the rest of the story, it's too abrupt and you feel like you're missing a cutscene or something- You may find yourself trapped... if you built your characters wrong, you won't be able to survive to certain parts of the plot and may even need to restart everything. I'm thinking about you, Nine Hordes..."
,Not Recommended,249650,12091246,"Posted: 13 September, 2014",all,MidnightsFX,"This game was terrible.To elaborate, the game draws you in with the idea of a turn-based RPG with an unkown and intersting story and encourages the idea of character customization, dialogue options, and all that awesome stuff.Its lies, simply said and done its all lies.1. You will be stuck with a pre-determined 'party', with pre-determined skillsets, there is no 'designing a party'.2. The story is predictable, you loose your memory and gotta figure out what you forgot...3. The 'dialogue/charisma' options  while changing minor things are so few and far between there is almost no reason to do anything but SMASH and kill everything.4. Mages can't learn new skills until you purchase books for them (which are extremely expensive, so you won't learn any new magics till mid-late game.) While I am on the topic of mages there is a checkbox at the start of the game which effective says 'magic abillity' if you select that, you get mana and can be a mage- otherwise you'll never have that option.5. The skill tree is the same for everyone, so your sword wielding guy will go into swords and use the same 1-3 skills the entire game. (but will have extra points so he can get the same skills as your... archer!)If you haven't decided to quickly run away from this game yet, there are more 'great' things about this game I can only hope you never find out. The ending is as bad as you think its going to be about half way through (and its almost 100% predictible from the start...).If you haven't fled by now, you either love torture or your so dense this game might be for you (join the other <7% that have played through more than half of this game...).If you want a game like this, go play Dragon Age I or II, Divinity (for gods sake its way better), or pretty much any other turn based RPG game."
