76561198007251417,Recommended,249650,11682012,"Posted: 12 August, 2014",all,Scamandrius,"Blackguards is a turn-based strategy game with strong RPG elements, rather like XCOM but with a much greater variety of character customization. (Though it has a reasonable story, you might be disappointed if you're looking for an RPG. It isn't open world, there aren't many meaningful story choices for you to make, and there isn't much customization available for your character's appearance.)The campaign is reasonably long, though the game doesn't feel repetitive thanks to reasonably varied fight scenarios and win-conditions. Early problems with bugged quests and translation issues from the original German seem mostly resolved at this point (I only noticed some spelling errors in the English version and had no problems with bugged quests.)Common complaints about the game focus on numerous loading screens and an unintuitive UI. I found the UI fairly easy to pick up myself, only issuing incorrect commands once or twice. Though there are a lot of loading screens between scenarios, each one lasted only 1-3 seconds for me so they didn't detract from my experience. People playing on systems using HDDs rather than SSDs may find the loading screens take longer and so are more annoying, though.I was worried by the relatively low Metacritic score for this game, but I'm glad I wasn't deterred. If you like single-player, turn-based strategy games that put you in control of a small group of specialized combatants, you'll probably like this."
,Recommended,249650,11685816,"Posted: 13 August, 2014",all,godsmackrrc,"In a nut-shell, you'' definetely like Blackguards if you are into turn-based, hex-based linear tactical RPGs. For one, i do!The combat is nicely done and obviously the strong point of the game - it works, and keeps you challenged (at least, up to now).The graphics are nice, but a little too cartoon-ish for my taste (and for the atmosphere the game tries to create).The story is good enough to carry you from chapter to chapter, although it's a little obvious in its twists.There are obviously a few cons as well:- The biggest minus for me it's the inventory, and the way it works. You don't get a clear comparison between your equipped item and another one, in your pack or at a vendor - this alone makes choosing weapons a nuisance at later stages. The inventory also becomes cluttered extremely easy.- Also a minus is the auto saving system. The game makes it that, quite a few times, you have to fight battle after battle, without possibility of resting&healing. And the autosave saves as you enter a new battle. This means that, if you don't take extra care, you'll end up (it happened to me once) in a position i hate most in RPGs - making some bad decisions in a 3rd-in-a-row battle, i had no chance of winning the 4th. And the autosave was only for the 4th. So i had to restart not only the 3 battles before, but the whole branch of the chapter (a lot of dialogue and cinematics included) - and i hate remaking choices i already made, listening to the same lines over and over again etc. They should have made an auto save for each battle, and an autosave for entering a chain of events/battles - this way, you can restart the fights without restarting the story itself.Anyway, all in all, is a nice game (and i bought it during a sale) - so i give it 7.5/10."
